Abstract

NEON Science is one of the leading companies in ecological research. They have collected a multitude of data on many different field sites on a plethora of bacteria. One site of interest was Healy, Alaska, and a bacterial phylum of interest was Planctomycetota. This project aimed to analyze the NEON data with a particular fixation to the Healy site and the phylum Planctomycetota using the Posit Cloud and R Studio software.

Motivating Reasons

The Healy site is currently undergoing permafrost thawing as a consequence of human-induced climate change. Permafrost thawing has a massive impact on northern environments, causing the soil to loose its ability to support plants (Osterkamp et al. 2009). An additional consequence of permafrost thawing is that it can release dormant pathogens into the environment, which can have a devastating effect on both the wildlife and us humans.

Bacteria in the phylum Planctomycetota are currently the topic of study for many biotechnology companies, as they can be a source of bioactive molecules. These molecules are crucial to current research regarding treatments such as bioactive glass. In addition, bacteria in this phylum also play a key role in carbon and nitrogen cycles, making them a topic of interest for ecological research as well.

Introduction

Healy is a NEON field site located on the northern border of Denali National Park, Alaska (“Healy NEON NSF NEON Open Data to Understand Our Ecosystems” n.d.). This site is composed mostly of taiga, with mean annual temperatures around -1.3 degrees Celsius, with the main vegetation present being shrubs and sedge meadows. The site sits at an elevation of 678 meters in a glaciated valley, and as recently been subject to permafrost thawing.

Planctomycetota is a bacterial phylum which are found regularly in both terrestrial and aquatic environments (“Planctomycetota” 2024). They are typically small, spherical cells that tend to associate with other organisms to form biological films, such as in algae and sponges.

Methods

Data collected by NEON researchers was meticulously analyzed using Posit Cloud and R Studio software. Particular attention was paid to the data coming from the Healy NEON site, and to data regarding bacteria of the phylum Planctomycetota. Unrelated data was filtered out. The Posit Cloud software was then used to create and display several different graphs and tables to make the data more accessible.

Discussion

The samples present in the NEON data appear to be of high quality. Most of the samples at the Healy site saw over 75% bin completion, and fell under 4.0 for bin contamination, implying that very little foreign DNA has made its way into the samples (“Confused about Bin Completion and Contamination” n.d.). The data for planctomycetota samples were not quite of the same quality as the samples at the Healy site, but still showed less than a 5.0 for bin contamination.

Planctomycetota samples were found across several different biomes in the NEON data. This can likely be explained due to the phylum’s versatility. Members of the Planctomycetota phylum are found in a multitude of environments, both terrestrial and aquatic, so it makes sense that these samples would be encountered in many different sites.

Many of the phyla found at the Healy site mainly resided in soils. These phyla are very versatile, and capable of surviving in many different biome types. Given the harsh conditions present at the Healy site, it can be assumed that selection here favors generalist organisms, and this appears to be the case for the phyla in these samples (Li et al. 2014).

Conclusion

The samples present in the NEON data were of extremely high quality, with high completeness and relatively low contamination figures. This could prove crucial when analyzing Planctomycetota samples for use in bioactive materials, or when observing the effects of permafrost thawing on bacterial strains. With all that being said, the work being done by NEON researchers could indeed prove to be very valuable for future research endeavors.
